ne:4615"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "MYD88", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9904302954673767, "span": {"begin": 571, "end": 576}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:51135"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IRAK4", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.995070219039917, "span": {"begin": 582, "end": 587}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3552"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.993324339389801, "span": {"begin": 602, "end": 606}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4615"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "MyD88", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.993190348148346, "span": {"begin": 660, "end": 665}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4790"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NF-&kappa;B", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9440540075302124, "span": {"begin": 767, "end": 778}}], "text": "The initial step in IL-1 signal transduction is a ligand-induced conformational change in the first extracellular domain of the IL-1RI that facilitates recruitment of IL-1RacP (Cavalli et al., 2015). Through conserved cytosolic regions called Toll- and IL-1R&ndash;like (TIR) domains (Radons et al., 2003), the trimeric complex rapidly assembles two intracellular signaling proteins, myeloid differentiation primary response gene 88 (MYD88) and interleukin-1 receptor&ndash;activated protein kinase (IRAK) 4 (Brikos et al., 2007; Li et al., 2002). IL-1, IL-1RI, IL-RAcP, MYD88, and IRAK4 form a stable IL-1&ndash;induced first signaling module. The binding of MyD88 triggers a cascade of kinases that produce a strong pro-inflammatory signal leading to activation of NF-&kappa;B reviewed by (Brikos et al., 2007; Weber, Wasiliew and Kracht, 2010).  &nbsp;  &nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:14:02 +0000 2026"}